      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA software (Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2) is validated commercial code with documented QA procedures, version control, and regression test suite.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical is a commercially validated FEA solver with ISO 9001-certified QA processes. Version 2022 R2 was used throughout; all analysts operated under a documented model management plan with change control. Achieved level equals required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems with known analytical solutions (Euler-Bernoulli beam, Hertzian contact) reproduced within 1% error.",
      "rationale": "Three benchmark cases — cantilever beam bending, cylindrical contact, and bolt pretension — were executed and compared to closed-form solutions. All errors were below 0.8%, confirming correct code implementation for the physics of interest."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates QoI change less than 5% between successive refinements; Richardson extrapolation GCI < 2%.",
      "rationale": "Four mesh densities were evaluated (coarse to very fine). Stiffness QoI varied by 1.3% between the two finest meshes. Richardson extrapolation yielded GCI of 0.9%. The production mesh (2.1 M elements, hex-dominant) was selected as the converged solution, exceeding the required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals below 1e-6 for all load steps; energy balance error below 0.1%.",
      "rationale": "Sparse direct solver (SPARSE) used for linear steps; Newton-Raphson with line search for nonlinear phases. Residual norms converged to 1e-8 or better. Energy balance error was 0.03% across all 11 simulated constructs. Achieved level exceeds required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent peer review of model setup, boundary conditions, and material assignments completed; checklist documented.",
      "rationale": "A second analyst independently reviewed boundary condition application, contact definitions, and material property assignments against the simulation plan. All discrepancies were resolved prior to result extraction. No use errors were identified."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum elastoplastic material model with isotropic hardening appropriate for Ti-6Al-4V; contact mechanics representation validated against independent literature.",
      "rationale": "Bilinear isotropic hardening (BISO) with tabulated stress-strain data from coupon testing captures the elastoplastic response of Ti-6Al-4V. Frictional contact (mu=0.2) at screw-block interfaces is consistent with published tribological data for titanium-on-UHMWPE. Model form is appropriate for the quasi-static loading regime."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from lot-specific coupon testing; geometric inputs from CMM measurements of test specimens; uncertainty in inputs quantified.",
      "rationale": "Elastic modulus (113.8 ± 1.2 GPa), yield strength (880 ± 12 MPa), and tangent modulus were measured from five dog-bone coupons cut from the same Ti-6Al-4V bar stock as the test constructs. Screw geometry was verified by CMM to within ±0.01 mm of CAD nominal. Input uncertainty propagated via Monte Carlo (500 samples)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 constructs tested; specimens traceable to production lot; dimensional inspection completed.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were assembled and tested. All specimens were drawn from a single production lot with full traceability. Dimensional inspection confirmed all critical dimensions within ±0.02 mm of nominal. Sample size supports the statistical acceptance criterion."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions match the simulation boundary conditions; at least two independent load levels or configurations tested.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single ASTM F1717 compression-bending configuration at one load level (displacement-controlled to 40 mm). Only one test condition was evaluated, which is below the required level of two or more configurations. This factor is identified as a gap; risk is partially mitigated by the large sample size and two-laboratory replication."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation inputs (geometry, material, boundary conditions, loading) demonstrably equivalent to experimental conditions.",
      "rationale": "FEA boundary conditions replicate the F1717 fixture geometry, grip constraints, and displacement-controlled loading protocol. Material properties are sourced from the same lot as test specimens. A parameter equivalency table was completed documenting each simulation input against its experimental counterpart, with no unresolved discrepancies."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison using E/uval metric; all QoIs satisfy E/uval < 1.96 and percent difference < 10%.",
      "rationale": "Three QoIs were compared: construct stiffness (E/uval=0.81, 4.2% error), yield force (E/uval=1.34, 6.7% error), and force at 40 mm displacement (E/uval=1.02, 5.1% error). All three satisfy both acceptance criteria. Comparison was performed using the ASME V&V 40 validation metric framework."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) are directly linked to clinical performance requirements and regulatory submission claims.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness and yield force are the primary mechanical performance metrics cited in the 510(k) submission. Force at 40 mm displacement provides a post-yield characterization relevant to fatigue life prediction. All three QoIs are traceable to the device design requirements document (DRD-PS-001 Rev C)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation scenario (ASTM F1717 bench test) is the same physical regime as the intended use prediction; no extrapolation beyond validated domain required.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity directly replicates the COU: the same screw design, same loading configuration, same material, and same QoIs. No interpolation or extrapolation beyond the validated scenario is required for the regulatory claim. Two independent laboratories confirmed reproducibility of the experimental data."
    }
